description:
This Cognitive Case File explores Overgeneralization, a common cognitive distortion that leads students to view isolated setbacks as permanent failures. Using a structured, research-backed approach, this resource introduces the TURN Method and Inversing, equipping students with practical tools to shift from a constricted, reactive mindset to an expanded, adaptive state of growth. 
 &nbsp; 
 Through the case study of Lebo, an engineering student struggling with self-doubt, students engage with thought experiments, cognitive restructuring techniques, and real-world academic strategies to reframe negative thinking patterns. The Fishbowl Conversation Method encourages active reflection, while TURN &amp; Inversing provide a step-by-step framework to challenge self-limiting beliefs and take actionable steps toward academic resilience and personal flourishing. 
 &nbsp; 
 Designed for individual reflection, peer mentorship, and group facilitation, this case file integrates evidence-based cognitive psychology, positive education principles, and practical student success strategies to ensure maximum impact in university learning environments. 
 &nbsp; 
 📖 Key Features: 
 &bull; Cognitive Distortion: Overgeneralization 
 &bull; Psychological Frameworks: TURN Method &amp; Inversing (NARMA &rarr; PERMA) 
 &bull; Core Learning Techniques: Thought Experiments, Fishbowl Conversations, and Implementation Intentions 
 &bull; Applicable Contexts: Academic struggles, career setbacks, and personal development 
 &nbsp; 
 This self-contained, ready-to-use resource is part of the Cognitive Case Files: University Student Edition series, developed by the Flourishing Future Foundation. 
 &nbsp; 
 Citation: 
 Abrahams, S. P. (2025). The Overgeneralization Trap &ndash; Applying the TURN Method to Overcome Overgeneralization. Cognitive Case Files: University Student Edition. Flourishing Future Foundation. Zenodo.

